    REVIEW DISPOSITIONS:

    P-01 [CRITICAL then PASS] credential_count dual form
      PASS , Reviewer self-corrected. "بيانا اعتماد" is correct
      nominative construct-state dual. No change.

    P-02 [HIGH then PASS] credential_count few/many/other terms
      PASS , Correct MSA numeral grammar: plural genitive for
      3-10, accusative singular for 11-99, genitive singular
      for 100+.

    P-03 [HIGH then PASS] Extra zero forms not in English
      PASS , Defensive and correct for Arabic CLDR. Android
      falls back to "other" if zero is missing; having it is
      better.

    P-04 [MEDIUM] Tanwin in "other" forms
      REJECT , Unvocalised Arabic is standard for UI text.
      Translator is consistent across all plural sets. No change.

    P-05 [MEDIUM then PASS] days_ago zero = "today"
      PASS , Good localisation choice. Natural Arabic.

    P-06 [HIGH then PASS] notifications_unread dual adjective
      PASS , Consonantal skeleton identical for dual and sound
      plural in unvocalised text. No change needed.

    P-07 [MEDIUM] Lone fatha diacritic in credentials_issued_today
      ACCEPT , Removed fatha from "بيانَي" to "بياني" for
      consistency with unvocalised convention used everywhere else.

    P-08 [LOW] Comment header inaccuracy for "other" category
      ACCEPT , Fixed comment to accurately describe Arabic CLDR
      "other" category.

    P-09 [LOW] verifications_remaining dual grammar , PASS.
    P-10 [MEDIUM] Format specifier pattern , PASS.
      Follows same pattern as English source.
    P-11 [MEDIUM] Glossary term usage , PASS.
    P-12 [HIGH] Potential crash with %d
      REJECT , Code-level concern, not a translation issue.
      English source confirms getQuantityString uses format args
      (English "other" has %d, "one" does not). Same pattern in
      Arabic is correct.

    COMPLETENESS: All 12 plural names from English source verified.
    All 6 CLDR categories (zero, one, two, few, many, other)
    present for every plural item.
    FORMAT SPECIFIERS: %d present in all few/many/other forms.
    Zero/one/two forms use natural language (no %d), matching
    English source pattern.
    XML VALIDITY: Well-formed.
    ============================================================
    -->

